00:05:41.360 --> 00:05:47.180
And let me give you an example.
I will give you one that builds on

00:05:47.180 --> 00:06:05.560
something we saw the other day.
We have seen ethylene or ethene.

00:05:33.000 --> 00:05:38.000
This is C2H4, and it has the
chemical structure.

00:05:38.000 --> 00:05:43.000
What we can do is turn this into a
long chain molecule with a repeating

00:05:43.000 --> 00:05:48.000
chemical structure in the following
manner. We can react it with

00:05:48.000 --> 00:05:53.000
something that will catalyze the
destruction of this double bond.

00:05:53.000 --> 00:05:58.000
And once this double bond is broken
we can flip it over to the other

00:05:58.000 --> 00:06:03.000
side of the carbon giving us the
opportunity to continue to link.

00:06:03.000 --> 00:06:07.500
This is done with a radical,
so we can denote the radical R.

00:06:07.500 --> 00:06:12.000
And I am going to put this,
remember, the unpaired electron.

00:06:12.000 --> 00:06:16.500
This is a radical with its unpaired
electron which we term an initiator.

00:06:16.500 --> 00:06:21.000
And so this initiator, when it
meets something with a double bond,

00:06:21.000 --> 00:06:25.500
reacts. The double bond is
something that could be turned into

00:06:25.500 --> 00:06:30.000
two single bonds. Let's
go to maximize bonds.

00:06:30.000 --> 00:06:56.220
This one has no bond,
broken. This one has a double bond.

00:06:56.220 --> 00:07:02.440
We could react the two and result
in the following,

00:07:02.440 --> 00:07:08.660
and now this goes over to here.
Now the initiator has attacked this

00:07:08.660 --> 00:07:14.880
double bond, built the bridge,
and now the radical is at the end

00:07:14.880 --> 00:07:20.220
here.
Well, ethylene is a gas.

00:07:20.220 --> 00:07:24.660
If this is sitting in a reactor,
gas molecules are colliding with

00:07:24.660 --> 00:07:29.110
